bib.title: Alpha Particle Emission in the Interaction of 12C with59Co and 93Nb at  Incident Energies of 300 and 400 MeV

free_txt: SD
SD. Subents 004 - 007 added.
Two complementary detector
assemblies were employed. These were conventional
charged-particle telescopes, each consisting of a stack
of two Si surface-barrier detectors and a NaI stopping
detector. This arrangement gives two AE-E combinations
for particle identification in each telescope,
corresponding to lower and higher energy regions. In
one of the telescopes the Si detectors had thicknesses
of 30 mu-m and 500 mu-m, while different thicknesses of
100mu-m and 2000mu-m were used in the second telescope.
The overall systematic uncertainty
of the absolute cross section values is estimated to
be less than 10%.
The targets were mounted in aluminium frames with 25mm
diam. apertures. These frames were mounted onto
an aluminium ladder that  fits into a target drive
mechanism at the center of the scattering  chamber.
Targets of 93Nb with different thicknesses (2.65mg/cm2
and 1.72 mg/cm2) were used in the measurements at,
respectively,  400 and 300 MeV incident energy. The
thickness of the 59Co target  was 1.00 mg/cm2. The
target thicknesses were confirmed by means of  the
energy loss of a particles from a 228Th source, to an
accuracy of  better than 5%.
Data were received from Dr. G.F.Steyn
